metadata.name: Choo Choo Train #46
metadata.description:
Even you can't take a plane to another country now, you can always take the Choo Choo Train. 

A Choo Choo Train could have more than 40 cars with 45 different styles. You will travel to at most 8 different places: The great wall, the pyramid, the metropolis,...and a hidden rare one!

30 color palettes, a rare train, different size and stroke style, and... more surprises! 

Drag the control bar on the lower left side, you can control the speed of the train as your wish.

[Mouse]
Drag the control bar: Speed of the train

[Keyboard]
[1] Hide the control bar
[2] Show the control bar
[s] Save in PNG

Made with p5.js

metadata.name: Window gratings 2 #59
metadata.description:
<Window gratings 2> combines 2 images in 1950s: The Window gratings in Taiwan and the Kowloon Walled City in Hong Kong.

Based on the previous experience of <Window gratings>, I rewrite all of the code and give it a totally different perspective.

More than 5,000 possible buildings & floors combinations
Tens of unique Window grating styles, balcony, and roof.
12 different color palette of buildings + 6 background.
3 different color mode lead to totally different images.

[keyboard] Press 's' to save PNG in original size

JT

metadata.name: Lepidoptera #46
metadata.description:
I love trying to capture the textures and colors found in nature and reproduce them with code. Lepidoptera is inspired by the species of the same name.

Features include: color palette, medium hatching count, large hatching count, noise offset, and noise level.

p5.js

metadata.name: StairWaves #157
metadata.description:
StairWaves is a generative collection imagining abstract stairs built in a wavy nature, with shadows being a key theme. While some waves are quite turbulent, others are just flat.

All shapes in the artwork are built using the same core logic applied in different ways. The method used to draw the waves is also used to draw the shadows, as well as the subtle textures on the surface of the waves. This homogeneous approach ensures a consistent and flowy feel to the final output.

StairWaves is coded entirely in p5.js. 

Controls (in live view): 
Press [2] to render 2000x2000px image
Press [4] to render 4000x4000px image
Press [s] to save the current view (default window size or 2000px or 4000px image)

metadata.name: The Fire Within #148
metadata.description:
This project is a study of ink, everything is generated in code without using any texture. 
It is an attempt to capture the ink bleeding effect and the look of the traditional Chinese paintings that have texts on top with modern approaches.

metadata.name: 8x8 Pixel Creatures #195
metadata.description:
Pixel art is a highly relevant art form, which rarely gets the kudos it deserves from the wider art world. 

I wanted to include some small pixel art creations in another project I was working on. However, I got a bit carried away, and ended up creating a pixel creature generator.

I came to like these little pixel creatures, so I decided to share them, and give them a life on FxHash - I hope you like them too. 

There are a bunch of variations, and a reasonable chance one or two styles may never be minted, so mint away, and I hope you get a rare one. Also, minters get a share in future royalties of their mints, which may be cool in any reality where they become popular one day.

I'll probably reference these guys on other relevant art I produce, when it seems appropriate.

Coded in p5js.

metadata.name: Dencity #651
metadata.description:
Dencity is a generative art project inspired by aerial views of cities with a high density of buildings. Its perspective effect, its perfectly imprecise lines, its subtle textures and its very advanced level of detail give it the appearance of a hand-drawn work.

Behind the visible art (the image) hides another form of art, an extremely complex algorithm capable of calculating and drawing in 2D each variation of the Dencity project. To draw a variation, the algorithm notably takes around 3,000,000 to 20,000,000 random decisions based on the hash of the mint and draws around 800,000 to 4,000,000 lines to create all the strokes and texture effects.

Made with ❤️, code and p5js.

metadata.name: ____ - Iteration 3 #258
metadata.description:
This project is part of a larger experiment that explores and celebrates the process of making generative art by progressively releasing iterations, working towards a final release on my main account (tz1RkYY3jr1ocuPdQqrRefr5FqoawKQsmBmD). The iterations will be titled ____ - Iteration 1, ____ - Iteration 2, etc. At this point, the number of iterations has not been determined, but more information will be provided as this experiment unfolds.

The final release will only be made available to those who have collected each iteration (using an allowlist), and will be released for free.

In live mode, add &size=<YOUR_PIXEL_SIZE> to change the pixel size of the image for export (Right click to save). For example, &size=4000 will set the width of the image to be 4000 pixels.

metadata.name: looking through a glass #154
metadata.description:
or life is a colorful mess
or not your usual generative forest

this art project continues the path that 'life is a (beautiful) mess' began with the representation of our lives using drawing lines that make repetitive patterns
as life develops, we look at it through the glass of our unique existence. every event, emotion and thought we experience stain our personal glass and conditions our regard towards the world that surrounds us
the cercles in every composition, represents that glass that we all have between us and the world, and the movement of the lines under it, life developing as we observe it
or it's just another figurative generative art project, as you wish...

10 different palettes
over 30 different color pens
single or multiple color glasses or cercles option
press [1], [2], [3], [4] keys to multiply resolution and reload the piece
press [s] to capture an image .png
press [r] to reload the animation
click the mouse to stop the drawing
doubleclick the mouse to resume the drawing

generative art created by mehno using p5js

metadata.name: Diffusion Walks: Series 1 #9
metadata.description:
Diffusion Walks: Series 1

first of all, zoom in. then zoom out. more.

implemented a modified "Image Random Circular Walker" 
to use sharp, rotating lines and jagged spirals instead of circular lines
by breaking radius/direction/angle a little bit, increasing stroke speed, 
and utilizing my own finetuned diffusion model outputs as inits for the new walking algorithm.


The new walk is some what of a frantic spidercrawl, accompanied by a shimmering dance.
I enjoy the glints of frenzy that this sort of motion adds to otherwise serene diffusion outputs.
Furthermore, there's something special about the output being revealed; re-distorting a guided
set of denoised images gives a lot of depth and momentum to the work for me personally.
It turns the process into a cycle.

fxrand() affects the init image, stroke speed, number of strokes, duration, stroke angle, and stroke sequence direction.

there are 25 image variations.
this is not about the images as much as it is about the walk.
there are countless walk variations.

duration, stroke angle and direction ranges vary as well.

there are 6 potential speeds.

as a result, hash variations will affect clarity, palette, init, and pattern of the token.

no recorded hash-unique features/attributes are printed on the token as a guide
please experience each variation's infinte iterations as their own realm
explore the variations, find different speeds and walker paths, enjoy the boundless variety in this set


zoom out to see the full image. zoom in for strokes. open live for easier zoom experience.
1280px by 1664px.

credits are important. when you play with a lot of things you made
mix them with things your friends made
and break things other people made
it is paramount to give all parties their flowers once
the art is made.

generated with my finetuned SD model, deforum notebook, and p5.js
credit to Vamoss for the original image walker algorithm (https://openprocessing.org/sketch/624879)
which was the basis for the new walker algo
credit to Stable-Diffusion team for original model which I tuned
credit to deforum team (which includes myself) for the deforum notebook

License included in License.md and p5.js file
License for Image Random Circular Walker and Diffusion Walks are both CC BY-SA 3.0

metadata.name: Minimal Monoliths #61
metadata.description:
Minimal Monoliths is a work mainly inspired by the use of AI as a creative tool.  I have a new fixation with monoliths as simple minimal structures just placed on random surfaces, so I iterated quite a few illustrations to sense the variations of shapes. 

Once I had an idea of what I wanted, I translated it into code creating something minimal with very fine lines that flow and then at some random point are disrupted by an emerging element.

Then in order to add volume and create a sense of depth, I increased the number of lines per iteration.

As Monoliths are considered elements deeply connected with nature I wanted to keep the lines and backgrounds within the spectrum of the earth's colors.

9 Color Palettes 
4 Backgrounds
Lines count [23,31,41,59,67,79,89,97,109] 

Made with ❤️ & pj5s

By CodeNFT (Clementine Novak)
October 2022
